article.headline: Temple 74, Fordham 60
article.story: PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- When David Hawkins' shot wasn't falling, Temple looked elsewhere for scoring. Mardy Collins scored 17 points and Dustin Salisbery had 15, helping the Owls survive a slow start and beat Fordham 74-60 Sunday. The Owls (14-11, 8-6 Atlantic 10) beat Fordham for the 19th straight time and kept alive slim hopes for an at-large bid to the NCAA tournament. Unless the Owls win the A-10 tournament, they're likely headed to their third straight NIT appearance -- a first in the John Chaney era. The Owls have won eight of 10 games, losing twice to No. 2 Saint Joseph's. Hawkins, the nation's third-leading scorer with 24.4 points per game, had his worst game of the season, scoring only 16 points on 4-for-19 shooting. He missed all nine 3-point attempts, misfiring on several wide-open looks. It was the first time this year Hawkins did not make a 3-pointer. "It's getting to be something we're starting to see a lot of," Chaney said. "Teams recognize we've got one guy that scores consistently." Hawkins has usually been one a one-player offense for the Owls, scoring at least 20 points in a team-record 17 straight games before that streak ended against Saint Joe's. Having his teammates contribute with clutch baskets takes some of the pressure off him. "It was kind of frustrating, but that would be selfish to get mad because my shot wasn't falling," Hawkins said. "We won, so I'm happy. It's supposed to be 5-on-5. When everybody plays like they can play, we're still one of the better teams in the conference." The Rams (5-20, 2-12) played one of their most competitive games of the season, leading early in the second half until the Owls pulled away with a 19-6 run. Salisbery put Temple ahead by two with a layup and a couple of free throws. The Owls forced a turnover and Tyreek Byard capitalized with a pull-up 3-pointer. Byard added another 3, making it 65-52 to put the game away. Michael Blackshear grabbed 12 rebounds and Byard scored 12 points. The Owls are 5-0 when four players score in double figures. "Guys are getting a lot of confidence now," Collins said. "They know they're getting left open so they're going out and taking the shots they know they're going to make." Byard and Salisbery led a Temple bench that outscored Fordham's 28-3. The Owls also scored 28 points off 15 Fordham turnovers. "They took advantage of our miscues," Fordham coach Dereck Whittenburg said. "We turned it over and they either scored or got the offensive rebound. We played OK in the first half and early part of the second. We had a chance." That chance slipped away as Temple rediscovered its stroke from the floor. The Owls shot only 28 percent in the first half, but bounced back to go 15-for-28 (54 percent) in the second. With the other Owls having strong shooting games, Chaney told Hawkins to focus on screens. "We got a few shots, Dustin came in and we swung it over," Chaney said. "He made the shots. Tyreek the same way. It's difficult to get David to understand it's going to be a bad night." Derrick Breland led the Rams with 20 points and Michael Haynes added 17. Breland hit a couple of 3-pointers early in the game, helping the Rams open up a 10-point lead. The Owls missed 20 of their first 28 shots from the floor before rallying with 3-pointers. Salisbery hit two during an 11-0 run and Collins sank two in the final minutes -- including one at the buzzer -- cutting Fordham's lead to 27-26 at halftime.
